-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">employ approximately 120</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,000 people and we transport more than 2.5bn passengers every year. Our company is comprised of five divisions – UK Rail and UK Bus here and First Student, First Transit and Greyhound in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">America</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are one of the largest bus opera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tors in the UK with a fleet of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">00 vehicles, and operate a fifth of local bus services. We carry approximately 2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> million passengers on our buses every day</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Bus division employs approximately 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">00 people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We operate across Britain, including 40</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the UK’s largest towns and cities, in close partnership with local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are the largest train operator; operating around a quarter of the rail market over every type of franchise, long-distance, regional, commuter and sleeper and carrying </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">310m passengers every year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our Train Operating Companies (TOCs) work with local transport authorities on a range of issues, including station investment and integration between rail and other local transport modes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the rationale for the Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">'s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government's approach? Are there better models?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FirstGroup believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decisions on local public transport issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, includi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng those around funding,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are generally best taken locally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This enables these decisions to be fully informed by the local prevailing circumstances and allows the development of meaningful public-private sector partnerships, such as Bus Quality Partnership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Agreements, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">South Hampshire Eclipse Bus Rapid Transit system and the Sheffield Bus Partnership.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For all parties, clarity around governance structures is key</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We support the creation of new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Transport Bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LTBs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and believe such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aggrega</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions should assist in decision-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making over wider areas, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but it is of concern that it has proved difficult for local au</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">horities and Governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to reach consensus on the boundaries of some LTBs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The shape and evolution of Local Enterprise Partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(LEPs) could well be a factor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here; nevertheless, there is a risk that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disagreement locally about the relationship between the LEP and the LTB and could lead to inconsistent funding allocations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Irrespective of structures, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is always scope for tensi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on between devolution and national policy priorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A clear example for bus operators lies with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statutory obligations placed upon service providers, such as with the English National Concessionary Travel Scheme (ENCTS)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bus operators are legally obli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ged to carry any passenger with a valid ENCTS pass without charge during the operating hours of the scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local transport authorities are legally obliged to compensate the operators for carriage of these passengers but due to the wording of the legislati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on, it is only an objective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ot a duty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o ensure that the operators are “no better and no worse off” than they would be in the scheme’s absence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Problems arise where the local authority takes a decision not to compensate operators fully for such trave</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This can arise as a result of the authority having an insufficient funding allocation from central government to cover this expense, or as a result of a decision by the authority that it does not want to pay any more to operators than a set amount</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ither scenario, both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the operator </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and fare-paying passengers can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lose out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the short term, operators may be forced to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cross-subsidise the ENCTS passenger through higher fare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s; or in the longer term, the financial pressure on operators caused by the sub-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">optimal reimbursement by local authorities could lead to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduced services and networks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the context of rail, the DfT published a consultation paper ‘Rail Decentralisation: Devolving decision-making on passenger rail services in England’, in March 2012;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with responses to the consultation being published in November 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government could helpfully clarify its views </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on devolution with respect to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resourcing, structures, responsibility, accountability and network suitability. In terms of resourcing, both tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ansport operators and local authorities will need to understand the level of funding and people that the Government is proposing as part of this process. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When dealing with rail particularly, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it would be difficult for Ministers to prescribe one structure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for all markets as geographic areas and passenger needs vary considerably. Also, local organisations need to be sufficiently flexible to respond quickly to changing passe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nger needs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As we set out below, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e would encourage Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to take a pragmatic and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> flexible approach in working on appropriate solutions for different rail markets.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the best way of dealing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> believes that there should be local accountability and that local bodies are the right ones to take such decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Devolving responsibility to lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cal organisations could result in quicker, less bureaucratic decision-making - also decision-making that takes into account the needs of local markets more appropriately. It could also provide companies and local authorities with an opportunity to work tog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ether to implement a more integrated transport offering to passengers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Different local bodies have different strengths and weaknesses when it comes to delivery. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the prime actor within a locality across a number of service areas, local authorities are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">well-placed to broker partnerships and express the will of local communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">odies which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enjoy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the engagement and support of other stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including private sector interests like LEPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be more successful in delivery of projects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">due to shared aims and objectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They should also be able to raise funds either directly through their stakeholders (if appropriate) or from outside third parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However this will require the establishment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a properly constituted decision-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making body</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with full accountability to its members and the local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">residents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and with appr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opriate governance and decision-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making structures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, LEPs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">require strong leadership and support, as well as the respect of the local business community and population, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f they are to survive and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fulfil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also note that there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">considerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> variation in the size and geographic scope of different LEPs; there will be no direct correlation of the scale and nature of transport scheme in any one area and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local LEP being of a suitable scale to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">take a judgment on it which satisfactorily reflects the views of all communities and stakeholders affected, either because the LEP is too big or too small.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Turning to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wider regional impact, where a nu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mber of local authorities come together</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">naturally means an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> scale, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potentially greater levels of resourcing or leverage become available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to those authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Of equal importance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, though</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is strong governance and co-ordination, such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensuring that responsibilities for transport and highways lie within the same body</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The new Combined Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emerging in the metropolitan areas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fit this template but where these responsibilities remain disconnected the result can be frustration of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> achievement of meaningful projects as the objectives of the different departments are not fully coordinated and may be working in opposition to one another.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In terms of rail network suitability, devolving responsibility to local organisations will always</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be simpler on self-contained networks where there is a lower interaction with other rail operators, such as Merseyrail, or the London Overground. Introducing devolution on more complicated networks raises questions on how local transport authorities inter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">act with other rail decision-makers in an industry that is already reasonably complex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, First ScotRail’s very positive experience of working with Transport Scotland to introduce new services and lines, and the general improvement in performance we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have brought to Scotland’s railway, including a 30% increase in passenger journeys since the franchise started in 2004</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, demonstrates how well devolved franchise letting and management arrangements can work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thus, we understand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and endorse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Secretary of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> State’s phased approach to devolution of the procurement of northern rail services to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recently established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Rail in the North </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(RiN) consortium of local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As the operator of First TransPennins Express (FTPE), one of two </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">franchises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RiN area, we are happy to work with DfT and RiN to prepare for the re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">letting of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">franchise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would refer the Committee to the evidence FTPE submitted to its Rail Franchising inquiry (RF 11) earlier in the year, which noted that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he separation of serv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ices by market type</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between FTPE and Northern Rail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has allowed many s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignificant benefits to be reali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sed for customers and taxpayers. It is important that any future franchising model for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">orth of England is capable of retaining and building upon these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improvements.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would note that, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n the absence of the Government Regional Offices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Government consideration of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the regional impact of major transport decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now lie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with central departments, in particular (but not exclusively) the Department for Tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsport. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies?</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As might be expected, our experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is varied, and often depends on the historic relationships between the authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In non-ITA areas especially, travel patterns and the nature of transport networks often predicates local authorities working together, but without a structural impulse it is sometimes hard for councils to take the initiative and look beyond their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> own municipal boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thus we applaud the efforts where this does happen, such as Transport for South Hampshire and the Isle of Wight which takes a holistic view of the transport needs of the area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conversely there are authorities who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for historical a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd/or political reasons resist deeper integration and closer working with their neighbours</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Naturally, this can limit the scope for partnership working from an operator’s perspective.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are always keen to support, and work with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local authorities on bids they make to access Government funding streams in order to im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For instance, we are proud to be the lead private operator partner in three of the five Better Bus Areas (BBA) which the Government has awarded (Sheffie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld – the first BBA, York and West of England)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBAs are a powerful mechanism for improving local bus services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Sheffield, South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive’s successful bid received an £18.3m grant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hich increased current Bus Service Oper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ators Grant by an additional 20% and was paid directly to the authority. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The bid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aims to improve access to jobs and services across the Sheffield City Council area.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The funding awarded allowed i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprovements to infrastructure used by routes in the city centr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprovements to traffic control to reduce bottlenecks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">audio visual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information for passengers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on buses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meet the Government’s criteria, the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">had to demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ood value for money</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atronage growth and emissi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on benefits; reduced wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">journey times</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; and have the s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upport of local operators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another example is of Wiltshire County Council’s successfully bid to the Government’s Local Sustainable Transport Fund (LSTF) for £4.2million to improve rail connectivity in the county, by inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reasing services between Swindon and Westbury, serving the local stations of Trowbridge and Melksham and allowing for mainline connections to London, South Wales, Bath and Bristol. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First Great Western </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(FGW) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">worked closely with Wiltshire CC and Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to develop the bid, and plan the new services, including the introd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uction of special reduced rate ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">route Melksham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fares, which offer a cheaper alternative to the previous fares on the route.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The LSTF application was approved in May 2012 and as well as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the funding for a two</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hourly weekday service (and five additional Sunday services), the grant allows for station improvements, including increased car parking, improvements to pedestrian and highways signage, cycle paths and a connecting community bus serv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ice.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> grant enables Wiltshire to fund the services for three years from December 2013. During this period Wiltshire Council, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FGW </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the Trans Wilts Rail User Group work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> together to promote the new services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he new services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">began </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on 8 December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2013 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there has been strong support from the community and high passenger numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">use of alternative funding streams?</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Partnership working has long been promoted by First as the way to secure improvements to public transport systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where relationships are good between the public and private sector, and shared aims and objectives can be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> identified, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we seek to move beyond simple one-off transactions (providing new buses to run on new bus lanes, for example) to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a joint investment programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Identification of bus patronage growth potential and a consequent return on capital can act as a cat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alyst for private sector investment in infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the past we have used legally binding public-private partnership agreements to drive improvements in bus infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Three major schemes delivered in such a manner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Manchester Road guided busway in Bradford, the Elite East Leeds guided busway and Glasgow Streamline, all involving First as part of its “Twin Track” initiative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first two </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schemes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">had significant private sector contributions to infrastructure cos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts as well as fleets of new vehicles and investment in driver training, information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and marketing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Glasgow </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contributed considerable funding for improved traffic signal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing including bus priority, and an automatic vehicle location and real time passen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ger information system on corridors where physical infrastructure was provided and funded by the local authority, as well as new vehicles.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">More recently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the concept of sharing the benefits of growth resulting from increased patronage has been reintroduce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d into quality partnership agreements such as that underpinning the South Hampshire Eclipse </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bus Rapid Transport (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This will use additional profits to fund improvements and extensions to the BRT system to complement local authority funding. This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be a successful model employed elsewhere.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We occasionally access alternative funding steams to support additional services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, a joint bid to the European Union’s Inter Regional IVB project fund has allowed FGW to add six additional rail se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rvices to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Riviera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> line in Devon. The bid formed part of an international Citizens’ Rail project to develop local and regional railways in the UK, France, Germany and the Netherlands.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The EU funding covers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">half </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the cost of the project, with the balance for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Riviera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Line services covered by Devon County Council and Torbay </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, along with FGW and the Devon and Cornwall Community Rail Partnership (DCRP), who led the bid. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The funding covers a single unit,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which will provide six additional trains a day each weekday between Paignton and Newton Abbot, with two services extended to Exeter. The services run along the coastal railway with some of the most scenic rail views in the UK, and covers Torbay, the secon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d largest conurbation west of Bristol (second to Plymouth) which has over a million staying visitors a year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As part of the agreement, station improvements worth £390,000 will also be delivered. The new services started on 9 December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">further example of a private-sector led bid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the funding proposal and consortium First Hull Trains </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(FHT) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is leading to electrify a section of line between Selby and Hull which is outside Network Rail’s plans for electrification in Control Periods 4 and 5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This £100m scheme will see 70 miles of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">route </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electrified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">result in more reliable services, with the potential of faster journey times for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">customers, greater operational certainty for F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and sustainable improvements for other passenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r and freight operating companies (for instance, gauge improvements for freight will improve opportunities of the Humber Ports)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FHT is leading a consortium which includes Hull City Council, East Riding of Yorkshire Council, Humber LEP, as well industry p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">artners like Network Rail and Amey, central Government and financial institutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Driven </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by First Hull Trains, all partners are working together to tackle financing, construction, industry regulatory matters and on-going maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As an Open Access ope</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rator First Hull Trains is a wholly commercial operation which receives no public funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thus, we are well-placed and incentivised to broker a partnership between local authorities, local businesses and key industry stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On 12 December 2013, the DfT announced that this scheme would be subject to further consideration by a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">joint taskforce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which is exploring further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electrification in the north</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">countability for local decision-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">making on transpor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t expenditure?</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For both bus and rail sectors, from our experience it is clear that many passengers, representative bodies and even elected representatives (at all levels) are not clear about the different roles and responsibilities different organisations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have in the provision of public transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The complexity of both sectors is both symptom and cause of the opacity for which passengers and members of the public sometimes criticise both public and private sector stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ironically, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in some areas, th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is opacity is increased by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the presence of an additional, dedicated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tier of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment, namely ITAs and PTEs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thus, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">usefully </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">set out the areas of responsibility between national and local organisations by setting out which organisation is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accountable for each aspect of transport policy including areas such as fares policy. This would help transport operators and ultimately passengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It could also help to raise public awareness of customer bodies like Passenger Focus and Bus Users UK.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> terms of accountability within the sector, l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocal transport authorities should have sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">weight and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">powers to influence larger organisations such as Netw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ork Rail. Local decision-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">makers have to be able to influence such an organisation to represent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the interests of passengers adequately.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, we would add that our experience of interacting with transport authorities decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making is variable, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">depending upon local authority structure and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience of ability and experience of officers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government seek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to devolve more responsibility and funding to the local level, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they must be able to guarantee that local bodies have the skills and resources to ensure decision-making is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">object</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ive, transparent and controlled.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6</span></p></div></body></html>